The main lipoprotein secreted from the liver is chylomicrons, which transport dietary fats to peripheral tissues. Chylomicrons are formed when dietary fats are packaged by pancreatic lipase and secreted from the stomach and intestine. In the circulation, chylomicrons serve as carriers for dietary lipids. Chylomicrons are cleared from the circulation by receptor-mediated endocytosis in peripheral tissues.
